Exercise description

In this exercise we will cover some image analysis with Python. You will learn how to:

  • load and display images
  • slice individual color bands
  • change the color space of an image
  • filter some features like green canopy cover
  • Apply basic thresholding techniques for image segmentation

Computing green canopy cover

In this step we will implement the routine used by the Canopeo app (Patrignani and Ochsner, 2015)

In [22]:
# Canopeo routine
#np.seterr(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore')

RG_ratio = R/G
BG_ratio = B/G
ExG = 2*G - R - B

<ipython-input-22-604882a464c8>:4: RuntimeWarning: divide by zero encountered in true_divide
  RG_ratio = R/G
<ipython-input-22-604882a464c8>:5: RuntimeWarning: invalid value encountered in true_divide
  BG_ratio = B/G

Warnings don't stop execution, but should not be ignored. Enabling the line np.seterr(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore') will remove the warning message, but I personally prefer to keep it as a reminder that we are getting values out of range.

In [24]:
# Replace infinity values as a consequence of the division by zero by a placeholder that won't affect our goal.
# Since we know that ratios of about 0.95 are effective for classifying green cover, then a placeholder of 10 should
# not have any impact on the thresholding.

inf_placeholder = 10
RG_ratio = np.where(np.isinf(RG_ratio), inf_placeholder , RG_ratio);
BG_ratio = np.where(np.isinf(BG_ratio), inf_placeholder , BG_ratio);

Define a function

In [31]:
## Define a function

# We will suppress the message in the function to avoid the message every time we call the function
np.seterr(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore')

def canopeo(img, RG=0.95, BG=0.95, EG=20):
    """Function for quantifying green canopy cover"""
   
    RG_ratio = img[:,:,0] / img[:,:,1]
    RG_ratio = np.where(np.isinf(RG_ratio), 10, RG_ratio);
    
    BG_ratio = img[:,:,2] / img[:,:,1]
    BG_ratio = np.where(np.isinf(BG_ratio), 10, BG_ratio);
    
    ExG = 2*img[:,:,1] - img[:,:,0] - img[:,:,2]
    BW = np.logical_and(RG_ratio < RG, BG_ratio < BG, ExG > EG)
    canopy_cover = np.sum(BW.flatten()) / BW.size * 100
    return round(canopy_cover,2)

Read multiple images

Now that we have a function we can re-use the code to process multiple images.

In [43]:
## Load multiple images
import glob
import pprint as pp
import pandas as pd

filenames = sorted(glob.glob('*.jpg'))
print(filenames)

['soybeans_20200819_090000.jpg', 'soybeans_20200819_120000.jpg', 'soybeans_20200819_150000.jpg', 'soybeans_20200819_180000.jpg']
In [44]:
CC = {'filename':[], 'timestamp': [], 'CC':[]}
for file in filenames:
    I = plt.imread(file)
    CC['filename'].append(file)
    CC['CC'].append(canopeo(I))
    
    # Not the most elegant solution, 
    # but it works without a separate module or more complex statements
    file_no_ext = file.split('.') # First split string at the period
    file_no_ext_parts = file_no_ext[0].split('_') # Then split filename at each underscore
    timestamp_str = file_no_ext_parts[1] + file_no_ext_parts[2]
    timestamp = pd.to_datetime(timestamp_str, format='%Y%m%d%H%M%S')
    CC['timestamp'].append(timestamp)

pp.pprint(CC)

{'CC': [66.32, 54.37, 43.14, 61.13],
 'filename': ['soybeans_20200819_090000.jpg',
              'soybeans_20200819_120000.jpg',
              'soybeans_20200819_150000.jpg',
              'soybeans_20200819_180000.jpg'],
 'timestamp': [Timestamp('2020-08-19 09:00:00'),
               Timestamp('2020-08-19 12:00:00'),
               Timestamp('2020-08-19 15:00:00'),
               Timestamp('2020-08-19 18:00:00')]}

Where to go from here

Python has a large ecosystem of libraries and I'm sure that there is one for your project. Below is a not exhaustive list of well-established modules that may be helpful for your project:

  • Scikit Image: An extensive module for image analysis. Very well dcoumented following peer-reviewed articles and with a clear and easy to understand syntax.

  • Scikit-learn: a great and well-documented module for clustering, machine learning, regression, and classification.

  • SciPy: A keystone of the Python scientific environemnt. From signal processing, interpolation (the interpolation in Pandas is based on SciPy) to statistical analysis, this module is one the great Python gems out there.

  • Statsmodels: a module for implementing generalized linear models, mixed models, and analysis of variance. If you work with replicated experiments either in the field or the lab, then this module will provide the tools that we use in SAS.

  • Xarray: A handy library for multidimensional datasets like remote sensing images. The module handles files like GeoTiffs and NetCDF files.

  • Plotly, Holoviews, and Seaborn: These are three plotting libraries that are worth taking a look. Plotly and Holoviews provide interactivity. Seaborn is built around Matplotlib and allows users to create common statistical plots in one or few lines. If you like the style of R's ggplot module, then with Seaborn you will feel at home.

  • PyNotes in Agriscience: A set of Jupyter Notebooks for doing common tasks in agricultural sciences. While this is still udner development, examples use real datasets collected in the field and the content is aimed at students learning how to code.

References

Patrignani, A. and Ochsner, T.E., 2015. Canopeo: A powerful new tool for measuring fractional green canopy cover. Agronomy Journal, 107(6), pp.2312-2320.
